    • Method Detail

      • getTimeArgumentValue

        public static long getTimeArgumentValue(java.lang.String timeArgument)
                                 throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
        Get and validate the value of a time argument which is in the format <hours>:<minutes>:<seconds>.<milliseconds>. Note that all partial values can extend their unit range. So it's for example allowed to specify 75 minutes. If the passed (String) value is invalid then an IllegalArgumentException is thrown. Negative times are not supported. Specifying the number of seconds is always required. All other time units are optional. Examples: 
         0.10 = 10 milliseconds
 .500 = 500 milliseconds
 0.3600 = 3600 milliseconds
 1.3600 = one second and 3600 milliseconds = 4600 milliseconds
 30 = 30 seconds
 180 = 180 seconds
 5:0 = 5 minutes
 75:0 = 75 minutes
 2:30 = two minutes and 30 seconds
 2:0:0 = two hours
 1:30:40.100 = one hour and 30 minutes and 40 seconds and 100 milliseconds
        Parameters:
        timeArgument - the value of the (String) argument
        Returns:
        the value of the time argument in milliseconds
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
